{ Holding on to the extra pawn. 18...f5 had been preferred in the earlier J.Grant-D.Eggleston, Edinburgh 2009, but now 19.g5 Nf7 20.f4 would leave Black horribly cramped, since he can’t contemplate 20...e5? 21.Nd5 Qd7 when there’s even 22.Nf6+! gxf6 23.gxf6+ Kh8 24.Qg3 Nh6 25.Qg7+ and wins. }
