{ Now White takes over the light squares, but so bad are matters that the engines want to go 29...Rxg2!? 30.Rxg2, partly because 29...Bg6 would have dropped a piece to 30.f5! Bxf5 31.Bd5. }
30. Bxd4 exd4 31. Nxf5 Qxf5 32. Bd5
{ It certainly is a Sveshnikov from hell, Black having lost all the light squares and with his position riddled with weaknesses. }
32... Rxg1 33. Rxg1 Nh6 34. Qb6 Qd7
{ Unfortunately for Black, 34...Qxf4? 35.Qc7 would be an immediate game-ender. }
35. Qxd4 Qe7 36. Ka2 $5
{ Ding is in no rush, content to savour his lovely position. } 36... Nf5 37.
Qc3 b6 38. h5 Re8 $2
{ Even after 38...Ne3 39.Be4! Re8 40.Qd4 Qe6 41.Bd3 Black surely wouldn’t have survived. }
39. h6 $1 Ne3 { Likewise, if 39...Nxh6 40.Re1! Qxe1 41.Qxf6 mate. } 40. Re1
{ Yet again we see White developing as rapidly as possible. } 40... Qe6
{ Natural, as would be 13...Nc6 when White should go 14.Re1 or 14.d5 Ne5 15.Nxe5 Qxe5 16.Bf3 which supplied a definite pull and soon more than that as Black carelessly allowed 16...b6? 17.d6! Rb8 18.d7 Ba6 19.Qa4 in Michalik-Kohlweyer, Groningen 2013. 13...Rd8!? has also been tried and enabled Black to hold in Nakamura-J.Shahade, Seattle 2003, but 14.h3 Bf5 15.Re1 should retain an edge, and if 15...Qf6 16.Bd3 Bxd3 17.Qxd3 Nc6 18.Re4! followed by Rae1. }
41. Rb1
{ As we’ve already seen, this gave the teenage Simon a small but pleasant edge in Williams-Stummer, Budapest 1994. There Black completed development with 15...Nd7 when 16.h3 would have left Black unable to exchange and after 16...Bh5 one sensible idea would be 17.Rb3, preparing to double as well as possibly advance with g4, another 17.Nd2 Bxe2 18.Rxe2 followed by Ne4 and/or Qa4, retaining a pull on account of White’s more active pieces. }
